solution.p:
We equate the two expressions for r and solve for \theta.
    r=2+2\sin (\theta) \amp = r=2+2\cos (\theta)
        \sin (\theta) \amp = \cos (\theta)  \amp \amp \blert{\text{Divide both sides by } \cos(\theta).}
        \tan (\theta) \amp = 1  \amp \amp \blert{\text{Solve for }\theta.}
        \theta\amp = \dfrac{\pi}{4},~\dfrac{5\pi}{4}

We evaluate either expression for r to find the other coordinate of the intersection point.
    \text{when}~~~~\theta = \dfrac{\pi}{4},~~~~r = 2 + 2\sin \left(\dfrac{\pi}{4}\right) = 2 + \left(\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right) = 2 + \sqrt{2}
        \text{when}~~~~\theta = \dfrac{5\pi}{4},~~~~r = 2 + 2\sin \left(\dfrac{5\pi}{4}\right) = 2 + \left(\dfrac{-1}{\sqrt{2}}\right) = 2 - \sqrt{2}

